The Familiar at the New Anti-Semitism
Why do so many survivors of the Holocaust sense emerging threats to Judaism before they become broadly visible?
Because they know that seemingly "innocent" hints can turn into accusations and ultimately lead to discrimination that is then enshrined in law.
Then hysteria sets in at this point.
The survivors sound the alarm because they know what's at stake in the game.
They strengthen our democracies in a way that only they can.
We listen to the survivors so that we too may survive.
Since the first round of the French presidential elections, it is clear that we have every reason to listen.
Not only demagogues like Jean Marie Le Pen or other crude right-wing extremists in Europe cause problems.
In the 20th century, people who saw themselves as "intellectuals" were often stepping stones for fascism or communism without joining a party with the corresponding ideological background.
In the 21st century, we deal with people - members of the "educated middle class" in conjunction with mass media, politics, government, and universities - who condemn Israel in a language that often reminds one of the language used by theportuners of these anti-democratic movements.
These are not yet the majority opinion in the Western world - thankfully not yet - but they are the voices of a powerful and influential minority.
At this point, the example of the French ambassador in Britain should be mentioned: Not long ago, he titled Israel during a dinner party in London as "this fucking little country".
His vulgar expression is not particularly alarming.
More concerning, however, are the reactions to it.
Neither was he recalled by his government, nor did the government demand Blair's recall. The matter was dismissed as just another scandal in public.
The French press portrayed the ambassador as a victim of British low-level media and not of his own despicable attitude.
Unfortunately, the French ambassador in Britain has quite a few allies among Europe's elites.
However, Ambassador Bernard served us a purpose: Through him, it became clear how widespread these new anti-Semitic sentiments have become.
As a columnist put it so aptly: Israel has become an object of hatred whose name no one dares to utter.
We, however, must not only dare to speak about it; we are even obliged to do so.
Given the daily attacks against Jews and synagogues in France, we must not remain silent.
It is a shame for all of Europe that so many French Jews cannot send their children to school without worrying about their safety.
Anti-Semitic attacks are also reported elsewhere. In Berlin and London, in Switzerland, Italy, Sweden, the Netherlands, and in parts of Eastern Europe.
We must not remain silent about the fact that denial of the Holocaust is becoming more common. Just as much, we must not remain silent about the comparisons between Israel and Nazi Germany that antisemites and anti-Zionists draw.
During a Palestinian television broadcast, Israeli soldiers are depicted as rapists and cold-blooded murderers, while a Syrian newspaper wrote that we "must confront the new Nazi plague that is emerging in Israel."
The Mufti of Jerusalem said: "It is not my fault that Hitler hated the Jews. One hates them almost everywhere."
During the live broadcast of a Friday prayer on Palestinian television, the preacher urged Muslims to "show no mercy to the Jews. Wherever you are, kill them and these Americans who are the same."
What we should think about in connection with anti-Semitism is that it always begins with the Jews, but never ends with the Jews.
If anti-Semitism is not contained, it almost always leads to attacks on other groups and minorities and ultimately undermines democratic institutions and the rule of law.
The fight against anti-Semitism is therefore a task for Jews as well as non-Jews.
Currently, the points of attack in this fight are less clear than ever before, because a surprising aspect of today's anti-Semitism is its flexibility.
Although the goal of anti-Semitism remains the same - namely to attack the Jews - it nevertheless changes its appearance, its strategy, its rationalizations, and even its vocabulary.
Once it was Jewish religion that was the target.
When this was not successful, the Jews were expelled or killed.
As racial theory captivated people in the 19th century, the Jews were attacked because of their membership in a wicked race.
With the existence of the State of Israel as a source of pride and protection for most Jews, today Zionism is disparaged as a racist ideology.
I do not equate criticism of Israel with anti-Semitism.
Just as with other nations, it is legitimate to critically stand against certain political strategies and decisions made by Israel.
However, anti-Zionism is becoming increasingly similar to anti-Semitism.
Antizionists sometimes claim that they are not against the Jews but "only" against the Jewish state.
Imagine someone saying: "I am only against the existence of Great Britain, but I am not anti-British!"
Or if someone claimed: "I love the Swedish people, but Sweden should be abolished."
You wouldn't believe them.
It is difficult to love or respect a people but hate their state.
And yet, there are people associated with Israel who claim they can do exactly that.
In various UN organizations, insults towards Israel are on the agenda.
This demonization of the only democratic state entity in the Middle East is a key point of this new anti-Semitism.
When Israel is described as "the enemy of everything good and the source of all evil," within the UN, the "scourge of contempt" is circulating, as Professor Irwin Cotler, a member of the Canadian Parliament, puts it.
This constant portrayal of a nation as the enemy of humanity is in reality a campaign against the Jewish people.
So liegen the numerous anti-Jewish attacks in many countries the demonization of Israel with its use of anti-Semitic terminology.
Compared to earlier outbursts of anti-Judaism, today's anti-Semitism is less about attacks on individual Jews, and more about an attack on the "collective Jew," i.e., the State of Israel.
Such attacks have set off a chain reaction of attacks on individual Jews and Jewish institutions across Europe and Latin America.
Previously, the most dangerous anti-Semites were those who wanted to make the world Judenrein.
Today, however, the new anti-Semitism uses different tactics and often targets the State of Israel through demonization and propaganda.
The most dangerous anti-Semites of today are those who want to make the world judenstaatrein.
